"1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1315":"1315","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1318":"1318","about 1340":"about 1340","about 1384":"about 1384","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Scotland, United Kingdom","Johnstone, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfries and Galloway, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret DeGaarviach was born about 1340, in Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Andrew DeGarviach, was 26 and her mother, Isabel Fitz Alan, was 24. She had at least 2 sons with Sir John De Johnstone. She died in 1390, in her hometown, at the age of 51."},"et":{"about 1340–1390":"umbes 1340–1390","1340–1390":"1340–1390","1330–1383":"1330–1383","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1384–1455":"1384–1455","1315–1373":"1315–1373","1318–1361":"1318–1361","about 1360":"umbes 1360","from 1382 to 1383":"1382 kuni 1383","1330":"1330","       1361":"1361","1373":"1373","1384":"1384","1340":"1340","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1360":"1360","1390":"1390","1315":"1315","1455":"1455","1420":"1420","1318":"1318","about 1340":"umbes 1340","about 1384":"umbes 1384","Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland":"Annandale District, Dumfriesshire, Scotland","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Johnstone, Scotland":"Johnstone, Dumfries and Galloway, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1340–1390":"noin 1340–1390","1340–1390":"1340–1390","1330–1383":"1330–1383","1360–1420":"1360–1420","1384–1455":"1384–1455","1315–1373":"1315–1373","